SIMPLE: transcript
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Transcript
<hw>Tran"script</hw> <pr>(tr⟦acr⟧n"skr⟦icr⟧pt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>transcriptum</ets>, neut. of <ets>transcriptus</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>transcribere</ets>. See <er>Transcribe</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>That which has been transcribed; a writing or
composition consisting of the same words as the original; a written
copy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The decalogue of Moses was but a <qex>transcript</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A copy of any kind; an imitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Grecian learning was but a <qex>transcript</qex> of the
Chaldean and Egyptian.</q> <rj><qau>Glanvill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 3. <def>A written version of what was said orally; <as>as, a
<ex>transcript</ex> of a trial</as>.</def> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transcription</ent>⟦br⟧
